TY  - JOUR
AU  - He, Zhiguo
AU  - Khorrami, Paymon
AU  - Song, Zhaogang
T1  - Commonality in Credit Spread Changes: Dealer Inventory and Intermediary Distress
PY  - 2022
Y1  - 2022/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhac004
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 35
IS  - 10
SP  - 4630
EP  - 4673
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Two intermediary-based factors—a corporate bond dealer inventory measure and a broad intermediary distress measure—explain more than 40$\%$ of the puzzling common variation in credit spread changes beyond canonical structural factors. A simple intermediary-based model with partial market segmentation accounts for intermediary factors’ explanatory power and delivers three further implications with empirical support. First, whereas bond sorts on risk-related variables produce monotonic loading patterns on intermediary factors, non-risk-related sorts produce no pattern. Second, dealer inventory comoves with corporate-credit assets only, whereas intermediary distress comoves with both corporate-credit and non-corporate-credit assets. Third, dealers’ inventory responds to (instrumented) bond sales by institutional investors.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhac004
ER  - 



